   "source": [
    "**Methodology:**\n",
    "\n",
    "For this part, I created a copy of the merged dataset so I could work with it without affecting the original data. I then calculated overall descriptive statistics including the mean, median, min, max, range, variance, and standard deviation for the main variables like exercise frequency, physical activity, depression, anxiety, and stress. After that, I grouped the data into age ranges (18–20, 21–23, and 24–26) to make it easier to compare across different stages. I used these groups to look at how depression, physical activity, and exercise frequency change across ages. I also split the data by both gender and age group to get a more detailed comparison between males and females within each age range.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Findings:**\n",
    "\n",
    "From the overall statistics, most of the variables have relatively small ranges and standard deviations, which suggests that the data is pretty consistent across the groups. Stress level had the largest range and variability, meaning it differs more between groups compared to the other variables. Looking at the age groups, depression scores are fairly similar across all ranges, but physical activity slightly decreases in the middle age group (21–23) and then increases again in the oldest group. Exercise frequency also slightly decreases as age increases.\n",
    "\n",
    "When breaking it down by gender and age, there are small differences between males and females, but overall the values are still pretty close. For example, females tend to have slightly higher depression scores in some age groups, but the differences are not very large. Physical activity levels are also very similar between genders, with only minor variation. Overall, this suggests that while there are some small trends across age and gender, the relationships between physical activity and depression are not extremely strong in this dataset."
   ]
