   "source": [
    "**Methodology:**\n",
    "\n",
    "For this part, I compared depression score and physical activity across different age groups and then broke it down further by gender. I calculated the mean and standard deviation for each group to see how the values differ. I also created a line plot to show how depression changes across age groups for males and females, and a heatmap to visualize how physical activity varies by gender and age group.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Findings:**\n",
    "\n",
    "From the results, depression scores are pretty similar across age groups, with only small changes. Females show a slight increase from 18–20 to 21–23 and then a drop, while males stay more consistent and slightly increase in the oldest group. Physical activity also does not change much, but males in the 24–26 group show a noticeable increase compared to others. Overall, the differences across age and gender are small, suggesting there are no major shifts in depression or physical activity between these groups."
    "The scatter plot above comparing sleep and study hours shows no strong trade-off between two variables. Students with higher sleep do not necessarily study less. Both variables appear relatively independent, with data points spread across the plot. Both sleep and study habits appear to have a greater influences on stress levels than academic performance. "
   ]
